      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im having some trouble with my deadlifts. my lower back is killing me every time i finish a set but i dont really feel it in my glutes or hamstrings like i should. what am i doing wrong with my form?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are likely not doing enough of the \"squatting\" part of the lift, which means your glutes and hamstrings are doing all the heavy lifting while your lower back takes the brunt of the stress. To fix this, you must learn to \"squat\" your way up, keeping your hips low and your chest up, rather than just hunching over and trying to pull the weight up with your back. If you are unable to feel the glutes and hamstrings, it is a clear sign that your form is off and you are relying on your back to do the work.\n\nYou might be trying to lift with your back too much, which is why your lower back is killing you. A deadlift is primarily a hip-hinge movement, not a back extension. If you are leaning too far forward or rounding your spine, your back muscles are doing the work instead of your posterior chain. You need to focus on driving your hips back and squeezing your glutes hard to create that \"squat\" motion.\n\nTo make this happen, imagine you are trying to sit down in a chair with your back straight, but instead of sitting, you are pushing your hips back as if you were trying to stand up",
      "source": "target",
