    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. so i've been trying to focus on the hip hinge thing you mentioned, but when i'm at the bottom of the lift, i feel like i'm just struggling to keep my spine from rounding. how do i actually stabilize my core so my back stays safe while i'm pulling? like, what's the actual bracing technique?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are likely trying to brace your core like you are about to be punched in the stomach, which is the exact opposite of what you need. To stabilize your spine safely, you must brace your core like you are about to be punched in the stomach, which is the exact opposite of what you need to do.\n\nYou need to engage your deep abdominal muscles, specifically your transverse abdominis, to create a rigid \"corset\" around your spine. This is not just about holding your breath; it is about feeling your belly button pull in toward your spine, creating a tight, cylindrical shell that protects your lumbar vertebrae from the shear forces of the lift.\n\nThink of your core as a tight tube that holds your spine in place while you drive your hips back. If you are struggling to keep your spine from rounding, you are likely not engaging this deep bracing enough, or you are trying to brace with your lower back instead of your abs.\n\nTo practice this, try the \"pump\" technique: take a deep breath in, then exhale forcefully while simultaneously squeezing your glutes and abs as if you are trying to punch a hole in the ground. This creates the necessary intra-abdominal pressure to lock",
      "source": "target",
